The Telegraph - Calcutta : Business

 Sterlite one up on RIL in cash hunt

 OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT

 Mumbai, Nov. 16: Sterlite Industries (India) has unveiled India Incs largest capital raising plan: the non-ferrous metals powerhouse aims to raise Rs 12,500 crore (approximately $3 billion) to fund its expansion.

 Sterlites proposal which was cleared by its board on Wednesday tops Reliances $2 billion fund-raising blueprint for its enhanced capital expenditure of $5.2 billion in its oil exploration and production business. 

 As part of the strategy, Sterlite has filed with the US Securities and Exchange Commission (SEC) for a $2-billion issue of American Depositary shares (ADS). This is the highest amount that any Indian company plans to raise through an ADS issue.

 Sterlite told the bourses today that Rs 12,500 crore will be raised through private placement with eligible investors, including qualified institutional buyers, foreign currency convertible bonds/global depositary receipts and American Depositary shares in one or more tranches.

 In its filing with the US SEC for the mega ADS issue, Sterlite said it would use the net proceeds from the offering for general corporate purposes, including capital expenditures and working capital, reduction of debt and for possible acquisitions of complementary businesses and consolidation of the ownership of its subsidiaries.

 Explaining in detail where these funds will be used, the company revealed that its current intention is to exercise the call option to acquire the governments remaining 29.5 per cent ownership interest in Hindustan Zinc or 26 per cent if the government exercises in full its right to sell 3.5 per cent of HZL to its employees. This will come after the call option becomes exercisable on or after April 11, 2007.

 Funds raised from the ADS issue will be used for its commercial power generation foray. The company, through subsidiary (Sterlite Energy), is planning to build the first phase, totalling 2,400 MW, of a thermal coal-based power facility in Orissa, at a cost of Rs 8451 crore over four years.

 The ADS issue will also be used to reduce debt of up to Rs 667 crore and acquire complementary businesses.




